==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Old-fashioned
<hw>Old`-fash"ioned</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Formed
according to old or obsolete fashion or pattern; belonging to or
characteristic of times past; adhering to old customs, styles, or ideas;
<as>as, an <ex>old-fashioned</ex> dress, girl; <ex>old-fashioned</ex>
wire-rimmed glasses</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Old-fashioned</xex> men of
wit.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>old-fashioned</qex>, quaint abode.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unacceptable or suboptimum because of having been
superseded by something more recent; outmoded{2}; out-of-date.</def>
[Narrower terms: <stype>old-fashioned</stype>, <stype>out of
fashion</stype>(predicate), <stype>out of style</stype>(predicate),
<stype>passe</stype>, <stype>passee</stype>.]⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> antique, old-hat(predicate), outmoded,
out-of-date.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Unfashionably out of date; out of style.</def>
[Narrower terms: <stype>unfashionable (vs. fashionable)</stype>]⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> demode, out of fashion(predicate), out of
style(predicate), passe, passee.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>old-fashioned</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>old fashioned</ent>⟦br⟧
